# Conventional Commits

When proposing or writing a Git commit message (including one-line summaries), use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/).

## Format

- First line: `type(scope): subject` or `type: subject`
- Use a **lowercase** type from this set when it fits: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `style`, `ci`, `build`
- **Subject**: imperative mood, no trailing period, keep the first line roughly **≤ 72** characters when practical
- **Body** (optional): blank line after the subject; wrap at ~72 chars; explain motivation and breaking changes, not implementation noise

## Examples

- `feat: add room creation API`
- `fix: reject night actions outside the active phase`
- `docs: align MVP spec with discussion gate rules`
- `refactor: extract phase sync payload builder`
- `chore: bump Spring Boot and Redis starter versions`

## Do not

- Do not use vague titles like "update", "changes", or "fix stuff" without a type
- Do not paste an entire paragraph into the subject line; move detail to the body
